# Azveria Online Developer Guide

This guide covers the developer-facing workflows needed to safely maintain Azveria Online across local Docker, remote Docker contexts, and fresh server installs.

## 1) Core Stack

- Backend: Laravel 9
- Database: MySQL 8
- Realtime: Ratchet websocket server
- Deployment: Docker Compose with image-contained app/nginx/mysql services

## 2) Bring Up The Stack

### Local

From the repository root:

```powershell
docker context use default
docker compose up -d --build
```

### Remote Docker Context

```powershell
docker context use remote
docker compose up -d --build
```

This repository is already structured so app, nginx, and MySQL images do not depend on Windows-only bind mounts when using an SSH Docker context.

### Run Laravel Migrations On Remote (After Stack Is Already Running)

Use this when the containers are already up on the remote context and you only need to apply new Laravel migrations.

From the repository root:

```powershell
docker context use remote
docker compose ps
docker compose exec app php artisan migrate --force
```

Recommended follow-up:

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan config:clear
docker compose exec app php artisan cache:clear
```

Quick verification:

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan migrate:status
```

If migration fails with a DB host/connect error, confirm the `mysql` service is healthy in `docker compose ps` before retrying.

## 3) Existing Server Schema Updates

Fresh setups use the SQL in `database/init/001_schema.sql` automatically.

For an already-running server with an existing MySQL volume, apply:

`database/manual-upgrades/2026_04_12_account_chat_and_terrain.sql`

Example from the repository root:

```powershell
docker context use remote
docker compose exec -T mysql mysql -u root -p$env:MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD azveria < database/manual-upgrades/2026_04_12_account_chat_and_terrain.sql
```

If you do not have `$env:MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD` exported in the shell, pass the password explicitly.

This upgrade now backfills both schema changes and core reference data so old volumes match fresh installs more closely.

It adds or refreshes:

- `seafront_pct` to `nation_terrain_stats`
- `archived_at`, `deleted_at`, and `last_read_message_id` to `chat_members`
- `year_started_at`, `elapsed_hours_in_year`, `auto_increment_enabled`, and `year_label_offset` to `game_time`
- `player_visibility_rules` for Other Nations visibility control
- `game_documents` for the Game Information and Rules admin tab
- base `shop_categories`
- default `map_layers`
- default `game_time` row if missing
- `building_catalog` and `unit_catalog` starter entries
- starter shop items such as ore refinement and light infantry recruitment

Recommended old-database refresh process:

1. Switch to the correct Docker context.
2. Run the manual upgrade SQL.
3. Rebuild the app stack.
4. Clear Laravel caches.
5. Smoke-test login, Chat, Shop, Map, and Other Nations.

Example full refresh from the repository root:

```powershell
docker context use remote
docker compose exec -T mysql mysql -u root -p$env:MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD azveria < database/manual-upgrades/2026_04_12_account_chat_and_terrain.sql
docker compose up -d --build
docker compose exec app php artisan config:clear
docker compose exec app php artisan cache:clear
```

After the refresh, verify these old-database features specifically:

- Chat loads and `/api/chats` returns JSON
- Other Nations opens without missing visibility-rule data
- admin Game Information and Rules document list loads
- Shop categories and starter items appear
- admin Add Unit dropdown is populated

## 4) Account Management Scripts

Account creation and deletion is implemented as Laravel Artisan commands so it works locally, inside Docker, and on remote servers without using the GUI.

### Create a player account

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan azveria:account-create "Player Name" player@example.com "TempPass123"
```

### Create an admin account

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan azveria:account-create "Admin Name" admin2@example.com "TempPass123" --role=admin --no-force-password-reset
```

### Create an admin account with forced reset

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan azveria:account-create "Admin Name" admin2@example.com "TempPass123" --role=admin
```

### Create an account and force nation creation manually

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan azveria:account-create "GM Account" gm@example.com "TempPass123" --role=admin --with-nation
```

### Delete a player account

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan azveria:account-delete player@example.com --confirm-name="Player Name"
```

### Delete an admin account

```powershell
docker compose exec app php artisan azveria:account-delete admin2@example.com --allow-admin --confirm-name="Admin Name"
```

Account deletion removes the owned nation first, then deletes the user record and API tokens.

